  "text": "The ZNF91 family appears to have emerged in the LCA of humans and Old-World monkeys and published phylogenetic analyses indicate that it have undergone dramatic structural changes, including the addition of seven Zinc Fingers domains in the LCA of humans and chimpanzees, through segmental duplication [CITATION_1] . Moreover, the study of Jacobs et al. [CITATION_2] also suggested that the ZNF91 evolution is driven by an evolutionary arms race with retrotransposons. Their phylogenetic analysis of the ZNF91 family was based on the assumption that Zinc-Finger domains 7-12 in the human, chimpanzee, and gorilla genes has been created by a segmental duplication of domains 18-23 in the ancestor of these species (the hominine ancestor) causing the human, chimpanzee and gorilla to have substantially more Zinc-finger domain than the other species involved in their analysis. Additionally, they assumed, based on perceived similarity between Zinc-finger 6 and 7 in human, that these two domains are the result of a more recent than their proposed segmental duplication. However, because DomainDLRS directly models the evolution of the individual zinc finger in ZNF91, it allows show that the assumption underlying their analysis is incorrect as well as provide a more refined analysis, in general. It follows from our DomainDLRS analysis (Fig. 11) that the segmental duplication event occurring in the hominine ancestor actually created Zinc-Finger domain 4 and domains 6-10 from domain 16-21 (while we have not sampled Gorilla here, this event is likely to correspond to the segmental duplication event of Jacobs et al.). This means that the ancestor of human zinc finger domains 6 and 7 predates the root of the hominine tree in our analysis and, thus, there is no support for a recent duplication producing these domains. Moreover, domain 4 appears to be the result of a domain duplication followed by a domain loss. In fact, the ancestral domain order can be read directly from the reconciled domain tree in Figure 11 . In summary, DomainDLRS directly provides the ancestral domain content, and combined with an algorithm for inferring domain order at internal vertices, constitutes a powerful tool for evolutionary genomics studies such as the one by Jacobs et al. [CITATION_3] . HS_G91_ZNF1   PT_G91_ZNF1  PG_G91_ZNF1  MM_G91_ZNF2  HS_G91_ZNF33  PT_G91_ZNF33  PG_G91_ZNF26  HS_G91_ZNF34  PT_G91_ZNF34  PG_G91_ZNF27  HS_G91_ZNF10  PT_G91_ZNF10  HS_G91_ZNF21  PT_G91_ZNF21  PG_G91_ZNF14  MM_G91_ZNF18  HS_G91_ZNF15  PT_G91_ZNF15  PG_G91_ZNF3  HS_G91_ZNF3  PT_G91_ZNF3  PG_G91_ZNF8  MM_G91_ZNF7  HS_G91_ZNF31  PT_G91_ZNF31  PG_G91_ZNF24  MM_G91_ZNF12  MM_G91_ZNF6  HS_G91_ZNF20  PT_G91_ZNF20  HS_G91_ZNF9  PT_G91_ZNF9  PG_G91_ZNF13  MM_G91_ZNF17  HS_G91_ZNF25  PT_G91_ZNF25  PG_G91_ZNF18  MM_G91_ZNF22  MM_G91_ZNF5  HS_G91_ZNF11  PT_G91_ZNF11  PG_G91_ZNF4  HS_G91_ZNF12  PT_G91_ZNF12  PG_G91_ZNF5  MM_G91_ZNF8  MM_G91_ZNF9  HS_G91_ZNF28  PT_G91_ZNF28  PG_G91_ZNF21  MM_G91_ZNF25  HS_G91_ZNF16  PT_G91_ZNF16  HS_G91_ZNF4  PT_G91_ZNF4  PG_G91_ZNF9  HS_G91_ZNF5  PT_G91_ZNF5  MM_G91_ZNF13  HS_G91_ZNF17  PT_G91_ZNF17  HS_G91_ZNF6  PT_G91_ZNF6  PG_G91_ZNF10  MM_G91_ZNF14  HS_G91_ZNF22  PT_G91_ZNF22  PG_G91_ZNF15  MM_G91_ZNF19  HS_G91_ZNF27  PT_G91_ZNF27  PG_G91_ZNF20  MM_G91_ZNF24  HS_G91_ZNF26  PT_G91_ZNF26  PG_G91_ZNF19  MM_G91_ZNF23  HS_G91_ZNF29  PT_G91_ZNF29  PG_G91_ZNF22  HS_G91_ZNF32  PT_G91_ZNF32  PG_G91_ZNF25  MM_G91_ZNF26  HS_G91_ZNF13  PT_G91_ZNF13  PG_G91_ZNF6  MM_G91_ZNF10  HS_G91_ZNF18  PT_G91_ZNF18  HS_G91_ZNF7  PT_G91_ZNF7  PG_G91_ZNF11  MM_G91_ZNF15  HS_G91_ZNF23  PT_G91_ZNF23  PG_G91_ZNF16  MM_G91_ZNF20  HS_G91_ZNF2  PT_G91_ZNF2  PG_G91_ZNF2  MM_G91_ZNF3  HS_G91_ZNF14  PT_G91_ZNF14  PG_G91_ZNF7  MM_G91_ZNF11  MM_G91_ZNF4  HS_G91_ZNF19  PT_G91_ZNF19  HS_G91_ZNF8  PT_G91_ZNF8  PG_G91_ZNF12  MM_G91_ZNF16  HS_G91_ZNF30  PT_G91_ZNF30  PG_G91_ZNF23  MM_G91_ZNF27  HS_G91_ZNF24  PT_G91_ZNF24  PG_G91_ZNF17  MM_G91_ZNF1  MM_G91_ZNF21 0.0 0.5 1.0 (a) Figure 11 : Reco